    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>MTV and Antiwar Ads</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>MTV President Van Toffler letter explains network's decision for rejecting antiwar commercials (Mar 13 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>We feel that there was important context missing in your March 13 Media Business column about our rejection of an antiwar commercial.</p>
        <p>Few if any networks are creating and airing original issue-oriented campaigns that air throughout the day and express perspectives on both sides of this issue. MTV has created 47 different spots to date on this issue alone. So to allow an individual whose advocacy ad was rejected by all networks to be the sole commentator on MTV's programming content without any context or another point of view is simply unfair.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>We feel that there was important context missing in your March 13 Media Business column about our rejection of an antiwar commercial.</p>
        <p>Few if any networks are creating and airing original issue-oriented campaigns that air throughout the day and express perspectives on both sides of this issue. MTV has created 47 different spots to date on this issue alone. So to allow an individual whose advocacy ad was rejected by all networks to be the sole commentator on MTV's programming content without any context or another point of view is simply unfair.</p>
        <p>It is MTV's longstanding practice to use news pieces, public service announcements, videos, online features and long-form programs to educate, inform and empower our audience. On an issue as critical as the potential war with Iraq, it is crucial to MTV that we not only provide our audience with an honest, in-your-face dialogue, but also that we create a sense of community among those tuning in. We maintain our position of not accepting advocacy ads, a standard industry practice, and have a great deal of faith in young people's ability to take in unbiased information and decide for themselves.</p>
        <p>VAN TOFFLER  President, MTV and MTV2  New York, March 14, 2003</p>
      </block>
